title: For Sale:  HK MR762 A1 308 Win / 7.62 NEW! H&K        Free Shipping
postcontent:
Manufacturer: Heckler & Koch
Model: MR762-A1
Finish: Black
Caliber: .308 Win (7.62x51mm)
Operating System: Gas Operated Semi Automatic
Barrel: 16.5" 1:12 Twist
Weight: 9.9 lbs
Overall Length: 35.94" - 39.5"
Controls: Ambidextrous Manual Safety
Sights: Optics Ready, No Sights Included
Magazine Capacity: 10rds
Like its 5.56 mm counterpart, the MR762A1 is a direct descendent of the HK416/417 series, only in a semi-automatic rifle configuration developed for civilian users. Using the HK-proprietary operating system, the MR762A1 is gas operated and uses a piston and a solid operating ‚Äúpusher‚Äù rod in place of the common gas tube normally employed in AR15/M16/M4-style weapons. Pioneered by Heckler & Koch in the G36, HK416, and HK417; this method virtually eliminates malfunctions common to direct impingement gas systems since hot carbon fouling and waste gases do not enter the receiver area. The MR762A1 stays cleaner, reducing heat transfer to the bolt and bolt carrier, and drastically reducing wear and tear on other critical components. The service life of all parts is increased substantially. The MR762A1 uses a barrel produced by Heckler & Koch's famous cold hammer forging process. This manufacturing process uses the highest quality steel, producing a barrel that ensures superior accuracy, even after firing thousands of rounds. The MR762A1 is produced at Heckler & Koch's American manufacturing facilities from both American and German-made components.

title: For Sale:  Rare Italian Benelli B76 9mm - super accurate, NR
postcontent:
For sale is a hard-to-find Benelli B76. This is the "standard" model of the B-series pistols chambered in 9mm. They are famed for their build quality, accuracy and great hand-feel.

This particular gun is in pretty good shape. The only areas of concern are the grip frame, which has a nice patina on the front and back, and the left side wood panel. It has a small, seemingly stable crack near the screw, visible in the photos. It's been there since I got the gun, and hasn't gotten worse over hundreds of rounds, so I don't think it's something to worry much about. It would also be easily repaired with a dab of wood glue for peace of mind.

The bluing on the top back half of the slide is showing very light surface rust that was challenging to pick up with the camera, and is equally hard to see with the eye. The pictures below are an accurate representation of the condition of the gun.

The front sight itself is completely intact, but a bit of the white has been worn off. It's minor and can be seen in the second-to-last photo. It certainly doesn't affect the gun's performance at the range - thanks to the fixed barrel design and Luger grip angle, these pistols are extremely accurate and easy to shoot well.

While I'd say the cosmetic condition of the gun is around 85-90% (mostly because of the grip patina), the function is flawless on this example.

title: For Sale:  Hi-Standard Sentinel Deluxe, R-106, High Standard .22 9 shot revolver
postcontent: Here is a very nice condition High Standard Sentinel Deluxe. The serial number puts it at a 1966 manufacture. It is one of the more rare R-106's, predating the more common R-107's, but as far as form fit and function they are pretty much the same gun. These pistols are a great piece of Americana, the model was largely designed in answer for an inexpensive, high capacity, reliable, plinking revolver to be sold by the iconic Sears and Roebuck. These were the glory days of Hi-Standard, pre-1968 when Hi-Standard sold out to the Leisure Group, these guns were crafted for the discriminating target shooter and plinker alike. Unfortunately, like so many classic firearms manufacturers, today's Hi-Standard pistols are nothing more than a name, and are not half the gun that originally afforded that name. This gun is in beautiful condition; it still has the original presentation box, albeit with some wear and a small tear in one corner which extends a bit down the top. The gun has likely never seen a holster, there are a couple minor areas of surface rust, on the outer perimeter of the muzzle and just forward of the barrel stamp. This rust is not in any way affecting the crown of the bore, and I chose not to address it with steel wool and touch up bluing as this would likely only diminish the collectability of the pistol. The chambers and bore are immaculate, no rust or pitting evident. Minor turn marks on the cylinder, and good sharp edges on the hand, star, doghouse etc... Never been closed with the extractor extended, these 106's came with the spring loaded extractors so this was much less common of an occurrence. Sights are crisp and finish is in overall great shape for a gun of this year.
